\cf1 Questions : 58 What are the advantages of stored procedures, triggers, indexes?\par
\cf0 Answer : 58 A stored procedure is a set of SQL commands that can be compiled and\par
stored in the server. Once this has been done, clients don't need to\par
keep re-issuing the entire query but can refer to the stored procedure.\par
This provides better overall performance because the query has to be\par
parsed only once, and less information needs to be sent between the\par
server and the client. You can also raise the conceptual level by having\par
libraries of functions in the server. However, stored procedures of\par
course do increase the load on the database server system, as more of\par
the work is done on the server side and less on the client (application)\par
side.Triggers will also be implemented. A trigger is effectively a type of\par
stored procedure, one that is invoked when a particular event occurs.\par
For example, you can install a stored procedure that is triggered each\par
time a record is deleted from a transaction table and that stored\par
procedure automatically deletes the corresponding customer from a\par
customer table when all his transactions are deleted.Indexes are used to find rows with specific column values quickly.\par
Without an index, MySQL must begin with the first row and then read\par
through the entire table to find the relevant rows. The larger the\par
table, the more this costs. If the table has an index for the columns in\par
question, MySQL can quickly determine the position to seek to in the\par
middle of the data file without having to look at all the data. If a\par
table has 1,000 rows, this is at least 100 times faster than reading\par
sequentially. If you need to access most of the rows, it is faster to\par
read sequentially, because this minimizes disk seeks. \par
